// Title: React2Shell Suspicious File Creation in Temporary Directories
// Product: Microsoft Defender for Endpoint – Advanced Hunting
// ATT&CK: T1036 (Masquerading), T1105 (Ingress Tool Transfer), T1070.004 (File Deletion)
// Data Sources: DeviceFileEvents
// Description: Detects file creations in temporary directories that may be associated with React2Shell exploitation.  Attackers drop payloads such as `healthcheck.dll`, `setup_c3pool_miner.bat` and malicious JavaScript files (e.g., `setup_bun.js`, `bun_environment.js`) into `/tmp` on Linux systems or `C:\Windows\Temp`/`%TEMP%` on Windows【677298509385333†L1330-L1360】.  This query looks for these file names and other suspicious DLL or script files created in temp paths.  Combine with process information for high confidence.
// Author: Ahsan M.

let suspiciousFiles = dynamic(["healthcheck.dll", "setup_c3pool_miner.bat", "setup_bun.js", "bun_environment.js"]);
DeviceFileEvents
| where Timestamp > ago(14d)
| where (FolderPath contains "/tmp"
       or FolderPath startswith @"C:\\Windows\\Temp"
       or FolderPath startswith @"C:\\Users\\Public\\AppData\\Local\\Temp"
       or FolderPath startswith @"C:\\Users\\Public\\AppData\\LocalLow\\Temp")
| where FileName has_any (suspiciousFiles) or FileName matches regex @".*\.(dll|so|sh|bat|js)$"
| project Timestamp, DeviceName, FileName, FolderPath, Sha256, InitiatingProcessFileName, InitiatingProcessCommandLine

// Tuning: exclude known legitimate temporary files created by installers or update agents by filtering on trusted initiating processes (e.g., `WindowsUpdate`, `msiexec`).  You may also restrict results to files exceeding a certain size or containing suspicious file names.

// Validation: copy a benign DLL or script with a suspicious name (e.g., `healthcheck.dll`) into the system temp directory on a test endpoint; the query should pick it up.  Also test legitimate software updates to ensure they are filtered out appropriately.

// MITRE Mapping:
//  - T1036 – Masquerading (malware disguised as legitimate DLLs/scripts)
//  - T1105 – Ingress Tool Transfer (dropping payloads in temp directories)
//  - T1070.004 – File Deletion (attacker may later delete these files; monitor creation and deletion events)

// Recommended Alert Rule Settings:
//  - Schedule: every 1 hour
//  - Lookup window: 24 hours
//  - Threshold: >0 results
//  - Severity: Medium
//  - Entity mappings: DeviceName (hostname), FileName, Sha256
